\details{
The paper defines FSSD by choosing \code{J} locations \eqn{v_1,\ldots,v_J} and checking
whether the Stein witness function is zero at those locations. This manual
writes the target density as \code{p} and its score as
\eqn{s_p(x) = \nabla_x \log p(x)}. For each sample point \code{x_i} and location
\code{v_j}, the package builds the Stein feature
\deqn{\xi_p(x_i, v_j) = s_p(x_i) k(x_i, v_j) + \nabla_x k(x_i, v_j).}
Here \code{k} is the selected base kernel and the gradient is with respect to the
sample argument \code{x_i}, not the location argument. For \code{d}-dimensional data,
each location contributes a length-\code{d} vector.

Let \eqn{\Xi(x)} be the \verb{d x J} matrix whose column \code{j} is
\eqn{\xi_p(x, v_j) / \sqrt{dJ}}. The vector
\eqn{\tau(x) = vec(\Xi(x))} stacks the columns of \eqn{\Xi(x)} into length
\code{d * J}; this is the row representation returned by \code{\link[=compute_tau]{compute_tau()}}. For
two sample rows,
\deqn{\Delta(x, y) = \tau(x)^T \tau(y)
     = \frac{1}{dJ}\sum_{j=1}^J
       \xi_p(x, v_j)^T \xi_p(y, v_j)}
is the FSSD U-statistic kernel. The division by \eqn{\sqrt{dJ}} at the
feature level is why the inner product includes the \eqn{1/(dJ)} factor used
in the FSSD paper.

The test statistic is an average inner product of these features over pairs
of different sample points:
\deqn{
\widehat{FSSD}^2 =
\frac{1}{n(n - 1)} \sum_{i \ne l} \tau(x_i)^T \tau(x_l).
}
In matrix form, \code{\link[=compute_tau]{compute_tau()}} returns the \verb{n x (d * J)} matrix whose
\code{i}th row is \code{tau(x_i)}. The unbiased statistic above is computed from this
matrix without explicitly storing all pairwise inner products.

The reported p-value uses the asymptotic null distribution from the paper.
The covariance of the feature matrix is estimated from the data as
\eqn{\hat\Sigma = n^{-1}\sum_i(\tau(x_i)-\bar\tau)
(\tau(x_i)-\bar\tau)^T}. Its eigenvalues are computed, and null draws are
simulated as \eqn{\sum_j \lambda_j(Z_j^2 - 1)}. Large values mean the sample
and target score do not agree well. The \code{"opt"} variant uses part of the data
to choose useful locations before computing the final statistic.

This test is parallel to the KSD tests but uses a different compression of
the Stein information. \code{\link[=ksd_u_test]{ksd_u_test()}} and \code{\link[=ksd_v_test]{ksd_v_test()}} build all pairwise
values \code{k0(x_i, x_j)} with \code{\link[=stein_kernel_matrix]{stein_kernel_matrix()}}. FSSD instead chooses a
finite location matrix \code{V} and builds the feature matrix with \code{\link[=compute_tau]{compute_tau()}}.
Moving from KSD to FSSD keeps the same sample \code{X}, target score convention,
and kernel layer, but adds the number of test locations \code{J} and, for
\code{"opt"}, a training stage that chooses \code{V} and the built-in kernel scale.
